Project # 3: Ensemble Techniques - Term Deposit Subscription Prediction¶

Context¶

The data is related with direct marketing campaigns of a Portuguese banking institution. The marketing campaigns were based on phone calls. Often, more than one contact to the same client was required, in order to access if the product (bank term deposit) would be ('yes') or not ('no') subscribed.

Dataset¶

The historical data for this project is available in file https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/Bank+Marketing

Goal¶

Term Deposit Subscription Prediction - Using the data collected from existing customers, a model will be developed that can help the marketing team identify potential customers who are relatively more likely to subscribe term deposit and thus increase their hit ratio.

Attribute information¶

Input variables:¶

Bank client data:¶

  1. age: Continuous feature
  2. job: Type of job (management, technician, entrepreneur, blue-collar, etc.)
  3. marital: marital status (married, single, divorced)
  4. education: education level (primary, secondary, tertiary)
  5. default: has credit in default?
  6. housing: has housing loan?
  7. loan: has personal loan?
  8. balance in account #### Related to previous contact:
  9. contact: contact communication type
  10. month: last contact month of year
  11. day: last contact day of the month
  12. duration: last contact duration, in seconds* #### Other attributes:
  13. campaign: number of contacts performed during this campaign and for this client
  14. pdays: number of days that passed by after the client was last contacted from a previous campaign (-1 tells us the person has not been contacted or contact period is beyond 900 days)
  15. previous: number of times the client has been contacted before for the last campaign to subscribe term deposit
  16. poutcome: outcome of the previous marketing campaign ### Output variable (desired target):
  17. Target: Tell whether the client subscribed a term deposit. (Yes, No)

Data Insights¶

  • The above univariate analysis for categorical features show a data imbalance for the target variable with about 88% no cases and only 12% yes cases.Other features that show data imbalance are 'poutcome', 'default' and 'loan'. The rest of the categorical features are slightly uniform.
  • About 10 features are categorical and therefore we will need to apply encoding, with the exception of the target variable.
  • In this regard,both label and one-hot-encoding will be applied. The encoding to be applied will be based on how many classes.
  • This encoding will be performed during the the data preparation stage before applying the machine learning model.

Observation & Data Insights¶

  • The variables: 'age', 'day' & 'campaign' have a normal distribution.
  • The 'campaign' & 'previous' variables are slightly skewed to the right.
  • The 'pdays', 'balance' & 'duration' are largely skewed to the right.
  • The difference between the minimum values and the maximum values for 'duration' and 'balance' are very high, hence we will use boxplots to check for outliers.

Strategies to address data pollution, outliers and missing values.¶

  • No missing values were detected from the above analysis.
  • Data imbalance between classes was detected by using vizualization and the value counts function.
  • For categorical features, label encoding will be used to differentiate between categorical features that have more value counts than their counterparts as captured label encoding section.
  • Outliers eventhough not a big issue when dealing with ensemble models were detected and removed using the percentile method as captured below.
  • After removal of extreme outliers, the entries were reduced from the initial 45211 to 45205 entries as captured below:

# Removal of extreme outliers using the percentile method:
# Since we are using ensemble models that are robust in dealing with outliers,only extreme outliers will be removed. 
# Removal of the extreme outliers did not change the accuracy of the ensemble models as anticipated. 

max_threshold = df['balance'].quantile(1)

df[df['balance']< max_threshold]

min_threshold =df['balance'].quantile(0.0)
df[df['balance']> min_threshold]
#Remove outliers 
df2 = df[(df.balance<max_threshold) & (df.balance>min_threshold)]
df2.shape

(45209, 17)

  • Categorical features were encoded first and different weights assigned to the different classes based on their value counts. # Creating a function for visualizing classifier results
def visClassifierResults(model_w_parameters):
    viz = ClassificationReport(model_w_parameters)
    viz.fit(X_train, y_train)
    viz.score(X_test, y_test)
    viz.show()

    roc = ROCAUC(model_w_parameters)
    roc.fit(X_train, y_train)
    roc.score(X_test, y_test)
    roc.show()

Observation & Conclusion¶

By running different ensemble models while comparing different performance matrices such as precision, recall, and F1; Random Forest and Bagging models perform better compared to Logistic Regression Classifier or Decision Tree. Gradient Boost has also an accuracy of 0.90 which is similar to that one of Random Forest and Bagging model. However, Gradient Boost eventhough it has a slightly higher precision for the 'no' class, it does not have a better recall for the 'no' class as compared to Random Forest and the bagging model. Ada Boost has very low Recall and F1 for the 'no' class compared to Random Forest and Bagging model.

On the hand, Decision Tree and Logistic Regression are not robust as compared to ensemble models like Random Forest and Bagging. As such, Decision Tree has a high training accuracy of 0.90 compared to its testing accuracy of 0.89 and hence it is prone to overfitting. The Logistic Regression model has low recall and F1 scores for the 'no' class compared to Random Forest and Bagging model.

Therefore, we can conclude that Random Forest and bagging models give the best results on test predictions for this dataset and therefore will be the best models to help the the marketing team identify potential customers who are relatively more likely to subscribe to a term deposit and thus increase their hit ratio.

In addition, Recall will be the best metric in this context to ensure more customers are converting to subscribe to term deposit. In this regard, there is a high cost associated with false negatives and Random Forest and Bagging have better perfomance metrics that are good for predictions hence reducing this cost as possible. Random Forest has a recall value of 0.971 for the 'no' class and 0.422 for the 'yes' class while Bagging model has a recall value of 0.961 for the 'no' class and 0.470 for the 'yes' class.
